# 3D Scene Graph

A simple approach on 3D Scene Graphs (3DSG) as coding exercise.
[Detailed explanation of the task](./material/interview_code_exercise.pdf)

## Explanation: 3D Scene Graph
A 3DSG is a semantically rich and compact representation of a scene. It is commonly represented as a hierarchical structure with multiple layers of abstraction, such as a root node, rooms, objects and object parts. Each node contains semantic information and relation
ships to other nodes in the graph. This representation is often used in robotics
and computer vision to reason about environments in a structured way.

![Example of a 3D scene graph from  Iro Armeni, Zhi-Yang He, JunYoung Gwak, Amir R Zamir, Martin Fischer, Jitendra Malik, and Silvio Savarese. 3d scene graph: A structure for unified semantics, 3d space, and camera. In Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF international conference on computer vision, pages 5664–5673,2019.](./material/3dscenegraph.png)
